This isn't incredibly important, but Kitchen-Terraform is written in and requires tests to be written in Ruby.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/f172585eaa23b9edc40c5b73b066654e1bae7120"},{"sha":"54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: A better error message for custom variable validation

Our previous message conflated the requirement for a full sentence with
the suggestion to write in a style similar to Terraform's built-in error
messages, which created a sense that the system would actively reject an
error message written in another language.

There's no intent here to block writing error messages in other languages,
but there is a practical consideration that Terraform's UI output is
currently not localized and so consistency with Terraform's other output,
if that's important to a module author, will typically mean writing the
error message in English.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/54cc4dadf68b6e0f3ef52eb60f8267da9ce2a789"},{"sha":"b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"configs: Accept and minimally validate a "language" argument

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

[{"sha":"d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605","author":{"name":"Rémi Lapeyre","email":"953e8a3102147c156e7cfddb2d9937b841ad931f@lenstra.fr"},"message":"Use a global sequence to create the IDs for each workspace

Until now the default workspace for every project would have the ID 1,
which would make it impossible to lock them at the same time since we
use the ID to identify the lock. With a global sequence to generate the
IDs, the default workspace will now have a different ID for each project
and it will be possible to lock multiple unrelated projects at the same
time.

If an old version of Terraform tries to get the lock on a project created
with this new version it will work as we continue to use the ID of the
workspace, we just change the way we generate them.

If this version tries to get a lock on a project created by an old
version of Terraform it will work as usual, but we may encounter a
conflict with another unrelated project. This is already the current
behavior so it's not an issue to persist this behavior. As users migrate
to an up-to-date version of Terraform this will stop.

Projects already present in the database will keep their conflicting IDs,
I did not wanted to change them as users may be reading the states
directly in the database for some reason. They can if they want change
them manually to remove conflicts, newly created projects will work
without manual intervention.

Closes https://github.com/hashicorp/terraform/issues/22833","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/d81d521bcd4b22b31f238ffb4064eef305fab605"},{"sha":"45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/45b795b3fd02d5177666218c3703e26252eeb745"},{"sha":"47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remote provisioners require a connection config","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/47a682141a3d794f98035f4ef9fb0fe2014b764e"},{"sha":"2b252ac677f1d99adcf08202c3047be2478a1055","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27910 from hashicorp/jbardin/remote-provisioners

We expect that in order to continue to evolve the language without
breaking existing modules we will at some point need to have a way to mark
when a particular module is expecting a newer interpretation of the
language.

Although it's too early to do any deep preparation for that, this commit
aims to proactively reserve an argument named "language" inside
"terraform" blocks, which currently only accepts the keyword TF2021 that
is intended to represent "the edition of the Terraform language as defined
in 2021".

That argument also defaults to TF2021 if not set, so in practice there's
no real reason to set this today, but this minimal validation today is
intended to give better feedback to users of older Terraform versions in
the event that we introduce a new language edition later and they try to
use an module incompatible with their Terraform version.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/b5adc330751a4e2a7f5873ecb745349361cda5ac"},{"sha":"86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"views: Fix missing source in diagnostic output

The previous implementation of views was copying and embedding the base
View struct in each individual view. While this allowed for easy access
to the interface of that struct (both in the view and externally), it more
importantly completely broke the ability of the diagnostic printer to
output source code snippets.

This is because the `configSources` field on the base view is lazily set
after the config loader is initialized. In the commands ported to use
views, this happens after the base View struct is copied, so we are
updating the wrong copy of the struct.

This commit fixes this with a simple mechanical refactor: keep a pointer
to the base View struct instead, and update all of the individual views
to explicitly refer to that struct to access its fields and methods.

This is not a particularly satisfying solution, but I can't find
anything clearly better. It might be worth exploring the alternative
approach in the view for the new test command, which explicitly pulls
its dependencies out of the base view, rather than retaining a full
reference. Maybe there's a third way which is better still.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/86495f93cb7999e48622f8b600c2aa2c1e7678a3"},{"sha":"e9c7f37b8ca9391e8c5c6003da1067c704d530da","author":{"name":"Omar Ismail","email":"85f2d1241bb07ac3d4093b3bf17b36a6088a7b14@gmail.com"},"message":"Enable --auto-approve for Policy checks on Remote Backend (Terraform Cloud) (#27804)

[{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"}]

In particular, pybind11's dynamic casting for its classes is a noticeable overhead, particularly when producing and consuming many buffers. But for JAX buffers we don't need all the dynamism and we can use something faster specialized to our use case.

The cost is slightly greater code complexity, but I think it's not a huge price to pay in this case: we lose a few pybind conveniences for faster code.

Change-Id: Ib5f18930490db1c8574a28bcbe339f1b2e4b6dae","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/64dde7d21c38b25effd7db944063bfdd20485b5b"},{"sha":"fe8d7f69b0de2680469c2863dfd379eaae0209b7","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Use a hand-written Python wrapper for CompiledFunction.

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```

jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%  10.0µs ± 8%  -11.17%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

In particular, pybind11's dynamic casting for its classes is a noticeable overhead, particularly when producing and consuming many buffers. But for JAX buffers we don't need all the dynamism and we can use something faster specialized to our use case.

The cost is slightly greater code complexity, but I think it's not a huge price to pay in this case: we lose a few pybind conveniences for faster code.

Change-Id: Ib5f18930490db1c8574a28bcbe339f1b2e4b6dae","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/greedforgood/tensorflow/commits/64dde7d21c38b25effd7db944063bfdd20485b5b"},{"sha":"fe8d7f69b0de2680469c2863dfd379eaae0209b7","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Use a hand-written Python wrapper for CompiledFunction.

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%  10.0µs ± 8%  -11.17%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

[{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"}]

[{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"}]

In particular, pybind11's dynamic casting for its classes is a noticeable overhead, particularly when producing and consuming many buffers. But for JAX buffers we don't need all the dynamism and we can use something faster specialized to our use case.

The cost is slightly greater code complexity, but I think it's not a huge price to pay in this case: we lose a few pybind conveniences for faster code.

Change-Id: Ib5f18930490db1c8574a28bcbe339f1b2e4b6dae","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/PowerOlive/tensorflow/commits/64dde7d21c38b25effd7db944063bfdd20485b5b"},{"sha":"fe8d7f69b0de2680469c2863dfd379eaae0209b7","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Use a hand-written Python wrapper for CompiledFunction.

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%  10.0µs ± 8%  -11.17%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

In particular, pybind11's dynamic casting for its classes is a noticeable overhead, particularly when producing and consuming many buffers. But for JAX buffers we don't need all the dynamism and we can use something faster specialized to our use case.

The cost is slightly greater code complexity, but I think it's not a huge price to pay in this case: we lose a few pybind conveniences for faster code.

Change-Id: Ib5f18930490db1c8574a28bcbe339f1b2e4b6dae","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/64dde7d21c38b25effd7db944063bfdd20485b5b"},{"sha":"fe8d7f69b0de2680469c2863dfd379eaae0209b7","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Use a hand-written Python wrapper for CompiledFunction.

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%  10.0µs ± 8%  -11.17%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

Scheduler's heap implementation sometimes accesses indices that are out
of bounds (larger than the size of the array). This causes a VM de-opt.

This change fixes the de-opt by always checking the index before
accessing the array. In exchange, we can remove the typecheck on the
returned element.

Background: https://v8.dev/blog/elements-kinds#avoid-reading-beyond-the-length-of-the-array

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bvaughn/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"cbcc3f51413be0b0ec64b7f16fb67e2062c42a53","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Track which fibers scheduled the current render work

[{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"}]

In particular, pybind11's dynamic casting for its classes is a noticeable overhead, particularly when producing and consuming many buffers. But for JAX buffers we don't need all the dynamism and we can use something faster specialized to our use case.

The cost is slightly greater code complexity, but I think it's not a huge price to pay in this case: we lose a few pybind conveniences for faster code.

[{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"}]

In particular, pybind11's dynamic casting for its classes is a noticeable overhead, particularly when producing and consuming many buffers. But for JAX buffers we don't need all the dynamism and we can use something faster specialized to our use case.

The cost is slightly greater code complexity, but I think it's not a huge price to pay in this case: we lose a few pybind conveniences for faster code.

Change-Id: Ib5f18930490db1c8574a28bcbe339f1b2e4b6dae","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/smalltalkman/tensorflow/commits/64dde7d21c38b25effd7db944063bfdd20485b5b"},{"sha":"fe8d7f69b0de2680469c2863dfd379eaae0209b7","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Use a hand-written Python wrapper for CompiledFunction.

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%  10.0µs ± 8%  -11.17%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

[{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"}]

[{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

[{"sha":"7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Proposed new Suspense layout effect semantics (#21079)

This commit contains a proposed change to layout effect semantics within Suspense subtrees: If a component mounts within a Suspense boundary and is later hidden (because of something else suspending) React will cleanup that component’s layout effects (including React-managed refs).

This change will hopefully fix existing bugs that occur because of things like reading layout in a hidden tree and will also enable a point at which to e.g. pause videos and hide user-managed portals. After the suspended boundary resolves, React will setup the component’s layout effects again (including React-managed refs).

The scenario described above is not common. The useTransition API should ensure that Suspense does not revert to its fallback state after being mounted.

Note that these changes are primarily written in terms of the (as of yet internal) Offscreen API as we intend to provide similar effects semantics within recently shown/hidden Offscreen trees in the future. (More to follow.)

(Note that all changes in this PR are behind a new feature flag, enableSuspenseLayoutEffectSemantics, which is disabled for now.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/7c1ba2b57d37df165da0f19c65ccc174866b5af7"},{"sha":"d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update build-for-devtools script to prepare unit tests too (#21182)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/d778518998b290abfd21647dbd027118a9b5b88e"},{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/r4b3rt/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"}]

    The sample implementation of representative_dataset() in the full integer quantization section has a faulty cast to tf.float32.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/7fa7874186238ee7f1d2082f25b523e9c01cd4db"},{"sha":"64dde7d21c38b25effd7db944063bfdd20485b5b","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:Python] Use handwritten Python wrappers for PyBuffer objects, rather than using pybind11.

In particular, pybind11's dynamic casting for its classes is a noticeable overhead, particularly when producing and consuming many buffers. But for JAX buffers we don't need all the dynamism and we can use something faster specialized to our use case.

The cost is slightly greater code complexity, but I think it's not a huge price to pay in this case: we lose a few pybind conveniences for faster code.

Change-Id: Ib5f18930490db1c8574a28bcbe339f1b2e4b6dae","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/64dde7d21c38b25effd7db944063bfdd20485b5b"},{"sha":"fe8d7f69b0de2680469c2863dfd379eaae0209b7","author":{"name":"Peter Hawkins","email":"34b19541630131950b5f204f2c5f2c647a3a7475@google.com"},"message":"[JAX] Use a hand-written Python wrapper for CompiledFunction.

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%  10.0µs ± 8%  -11.17%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

[{"sha":"8a8b0bf847b8ef4248671d3343e9fbe68dd08d59","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command+core: Minimal initial implementation of -refresh-only mode

This only includes the internal mechanisms to make it work, and not any
of the necessary UI changes to "terraform plan" and "terraform apply" to
make their output make sense in this mode.

At the lowest level of abstraction inside the graph nodes themselves, this
effectively mirrors the existing option to disable refreshing with a new
option to disable change-planning, so that either "half" of the process
can be disabled. As far as the nodes are concerned it would be possible
in principle to disable _both_, but the higher-level representation of
these modes prevents that combination from reaching Terraform Core in
practice, because we block using -refresh-only and -refresh=false at the
same time.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/8a8b0bf847b8ef4248671d3343e9fbe68dd08d59"}]

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
```
name                 old cpu/op  new cpu/op  delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%  10.0µs ± 8%  -11.17%  (p=0.000 n=20+20)

name                 old time/op             new time/op             delta
jit_simple_dispatch  11.3µs ± 6%             10.0µs ±10%  -11.25%        (p=0.000 n=20+19)
```

[{"sha":"ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Bumped DevTools Chrome and Firefox versions in Babel config (#21185)

We have been building DevTools to target Chrome 49 and Firefox 54. These are super old browser versions and they did not have full ES6 support, so the generated build is more bloated than it needs to be.

DevTools uses most modern language features. Off the top of my head, we it uses basically everything but async and generator functions.

Based on CanIUse charts– I believe that in order to avoid unnecessary polyfill/wrapper code being generated, we'd need to target Chrome 60+ (released 2017-07-25) and Firefox 55+ (released 2017-04-18). This seems like a reasonable set of browsers to target.

Note that we can't remove the IE 11 target from the react-devtools-core backend yet due to Hermes (React Native) ES6 support but that should be doable by the end of the year given current engineering targets. But we could update the frontend target, as well as the targets for the extensions and the react-devtools-inline package.

This commit increases the browser targets then for Chrome (from 49 to 60) and Firefox (from 54 to 55)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/ee6a05c2bff30e423a98bc083209a5dca6965ec5"}]

A hand-written Python wrapper gives us a number of benefits:
* it makes it cheaper to cast `self` to a `CompiledFunction` in the `__call__` method, since we no longer need to use pybind11's dynamic casting logic.
* we can avoid building an empty kwarg dict even when no kwargs are passed, which is something pybind11 does behind the scenes.
* the change allows us to prepare for using faster calling conventions, e.g. METH_FASTCALL in Python 3.7 or newer, which would allow the interpreter to avoid forming a tuple for the positional arguments.

In passing, remove unused arguments from PopulateCacheEntry.

Benchmarks (N.B. incorporating the PyBuffer hand-written PyObject change as well):
